I think this’d be a Mulan that lives up to the original legend and reinvents the animated classic for a contemporary era. I didn’t dislike the one they made as much as some have but the wasted opportunities hurt.And I think my take would’ve done well in the US AND in China.

Mulan becomes a general and the great protector of the realm—the first kingdom to have power pass from a woman to a woman. And while at the end there’s intimation she and her rival have become a couple we also see her welcome a hawk to her windowsill as the night grows dark....

Torn Mulan decides she must stay. The witch flies off as a hawk. When her rival and unit burst in Mulan and the Dowager explain what happened. Though she had no intent to do so the Dowager agrees to take the throne until the emperor’s only offspring—a baby girl—comes of age.

He wishes to rid his kingdom of meddling women for good—his grandma included. Still she sacrifices herself to save him and is wounded as the witch fights back. The emperor attempts to kill the witch but dies in his own trap. The witch prepares to flee—and asks Mulan to join her.

Mulan saves her fellow soldiers from ambush using her new technique and trains them in it before leading them to foil the witch’s plans.The witch takes the imperial palace and is about to kill the emperor when the Dowager essentially an older version of herself thwarts her.

When the witch says she intends to destroy this patriarchal empire Mulan fights her and almost dies. She manages to crawl off to the forest and teach herself a new way of fighting inspired by the the Phoenix and how it rises from death. (Training montage!)

It’s then that she encounters the witch—think Asia the Invincible. Female androgynous seductive she explains to Mulan that there is no place for women like them who are not women in men’s eyes nor equal to men in their society; that the world must burn for the Phoenix to rise.

When her dad aggravates his old war wound and Mulan decides to take his place it’s her sister who helps her get away telling her to find where she’s fated to be. Mulan fits right into the army—despite discomfort in hiding her gender. Her size and strength make her a champion.

Disney clearly didn’t want to make a straight comedy—this is a war movie action/drama—so lean into it. Give us a Mulan who’s “different” not because she’s a pixie tomboy scamp but because she’s bigger than the boys in the village and can kick all their asses in an even fight.

Alright this has been your definitive Fast and Furious viewing guide. Go live your lives a quarter mile at a time. FAMILY!#f9 #TheFastSaga
12) Better Luck Tomorrow - An early Justin Lin film that spawned the character Han (a fave!) Not pertinent to plot at all. Skippable (but a fun heist movie!) #f9 #TheFastSaga
11) Fast & Furious Spy Racers (a spin off TV show) - even I haven't seen this. Totally skippable. #f9 #TheFastSaga
10) The short films (Turbo Charged and Los Bandeleros) - skippable #f9 #TheFastSaga

9) Hobbs & Shaw - It's unclear how much the spin off plots will influence the main series but A) I suspect it will have significant influece and B) it's just a delightful romp. Watch it if you have time wiki if you don't. #f9 #TheFastSaga

7) Furious 7 - yes yes yes yes yes yes yes(watch it!)This is maybe the best of the franchise? It's just so artfully bonkers. This is where the series truly found the door to asking you to not just suspend your disbelief but disregard it entirely & you're happy to do so! #F9

6) Fast & Furious 6 - Now we're cooking with gas. This begins a story arc you'll want to follow from the beginning & the flavors are all here. Watch it. (reminder: events of Tokyo Drift "actually" occur in this movie's timeline btwn the conclusion & epilogue) #f9 #TheFastSaga

5) Five Five - the ingredients are starting to come together. The Rock joins the cast and we start to see the intentional disregard for logic and physics that elevate the later movies into art. You can skip it if you're crunched for time but it's REALLY FUN. #f9 #TheFastSaga

4) Fast & Furious - a reunion of the original cast. This one hooked me back into the franchise after starting to lose interest after 2F2F and Tokyo Drift but ultimately it's a little dull. Skippable #f9 #TheFastSaga

2) 2 Fast 2 Furious - The first sequel. Skip it and read the wiki entry. There are recurring characters that originate here but the whole thing just doesn't have the FF magic. (though it does have the best sequel name of all time) #f9 #TheFastSaga

Sooooo... The Eternals. My gut instinct says that it was the perfect story for an eight episode Disney+ series; not a movie. Too high concept and too much story to tell in one movie. I didn't hate it but it was very disconnected.

The Eternals on the other hand was excellent. Probably the most beautiful MCU movie. After seeing it I'll admit that I'm a little baffled by the negative critical/popular response.It asks a question about "doing the right thing" that the MCU has explored but ...

... confronts it in a much more direct way. The other thing that really acts as a foil to previous MCU themes is the weight of responsibility for past actions.I've long thought that these are the central themes of MCU Phase 1–3. But The Eternals provides a way through.

A Cruella no início do filme é MUITO pobre e é visível que ela tem bom gosto mas não tem dinheiro para comprar materiais caros nem incrementar as roupas como ela gostaria. E isso é refletido nas roupas dela: você sente o material mais barato mais puído +

Outra coisa interessante dos figurinos de Cruella é que a produção decidiu não apenas incorporar o revolucionário dos anos 70...eles incluíram também referências de cortes e moda dos anos 90 e 00 sem comprometer o espírito "de época" do filme. +

+ e Cruella é uma personagem subversiva que "quebrava os padrões" e desafiava o status quo da moda em volta dela. Mesmo os seus looks mais "tradicionais" são carregados de uma agressividade e força traduzidas através do couro e das cores.

Cruella e sua tchurma são claramente inspirados no Punk e no Camp dos anos 70. MUITOS elementos do punk retrô são usados até hoje sem nenhuma necessidade nem de chamar as peças de retrô (Casaco de couro é ATEMPORAL bora combinar) +

+ fundamentais da narrativa é MUITO importante que os elementos visuais não sejam meramente acurados...eles também devem ser apreciados pela audiência contemporânea. Ou seja a produção de Cruella tinha um desafio: como fazer moda dos anos 70 +

Cruella se passa na Inglaterra dos anos 70 uma década onde a moda estava em evolução rápida.Ambientar um filme nos anos 70 é basicamente fazer um filme de época mas Cruella não poderia ser *apenas* um filme de época. Em um filme onde a Moda e a Estética são elementos +

Holy hell: Spider-Man: Across the Spider-Verse was just god damned near perfect.

In a world where Marvel had sole control of Spider-Man Across the Spider-Verse would have been more like (the still pretty good) No Way Home or the Multiverse of Madness where it would have been inextricably tied up in the webs of other MCU properties and characters.

Across the Spider-Verse wouldn't exist in a world where only Marvel/Disney controlled the rights to Spider-Man. It *also* wouldn't exist in a world where Sony had sole control of Spider-Man since Miles Morales Spider-Gwen & the Spider-Verse comics wouldn't have happened then.

Spider-Man: Across The Spider-Verse is one of the most artistically dense movies I've ever seen. Every single frame was a work of art. The animation styles seamlessly blending from 2D to 3D to mixed mediums to different styles from different eras was mind-blowing.
